# Tier 1 — after matte_composite TF-dispatch refactor
# Date: 2026-04-23
# Parent commit: d826e24 (post CI fixes)
# Hardware: AMD Ryzen 9 7950X
# Command: cargo bench --bench bench_t1_layout
#
# Refactored matte_composite F32 and F16 arms to use const-generic
# `MatteTf` trait dispatch. The per-pixel `match tf { ... }` inside
# `f32_eotf`/`f32_oetf` is now hoisted to row level via 12
# monomorphizations (F32/F16 × Linear/Srgb/Bt709/Pq/Hlg/Gamma22).
#
# matte_composite progression at 4096px vs baseline:
#
#                              baseline      after         net lift
#   F32 Linear                1.37 GiB/s →  13.28 GiB/s    9.69x  ★
#   F16 Linear                0.94       →   6.73          7.35x  ★
#   F16 HLG                  462 MiB/s  →    799           1.73x
#   F16 sRGB                 301        →    408           1.36x
#   F32 HLG                  529        →    717           1.35x
#   F32 sRGB                 365        →    461           1.26x
#   F16 PQ                   208        →    259           1.25x
#   F32 PQ                   248        →    288           1.16x
#
# Interpretation:
#
# Linear TF (no-op) hit 10× because hoisting the match unblocked
# full autovec on the blend-only arithmetic. The compiler-generated
# AVX2/AVX-512 pure-f32 multiply-add kernel is within 4× of memory
# bandwidth for RGBA-in, RGB-out.
#
# Non-Linear TFs get 1.2-1.7× because the scalar TF polynomial inside
# each `T::eotf`/`T::oetf` call now inlines cleanly but its own
# per-value divide/branch prevents the outer blend loop from
# vectorizing fully. Getting more would require calling linear-srgb's
# f32x8 rites directly via `incant!` — a separate piece of work that
# mirrors the F16C pattern we used for f16↔f32.
#
# All non-matte kernels unchanged within ±5% noise.
